To generate an unsigned 32-bit integer in C, you can make use of the `stdint.h` library and its data type `uint32_t`. Below is an example that demonstrates how to generate and print an unsigned 32-bit integer:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdint.h>

int main() {
    uint32_t num = 1234567890;  // Sample integer value

    printf("%u\n", num);  // Print the unsigned 32-bit integer

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we have declared a variable `num` of type `uint32_t` and assigned it the value of `1234567890`. You can change this value to generate your desired unsigned 32-bit integer. The `%u` specifier in the `printf()` function is used to print the value of the unsigned integer.

